1007594538423250944.text: 10/ Whereas in more open systems such as PoW & PoS, even if they are *arguably* more centralised because they tend towards power law distributions of control, they are less fragile because anyone can in practice contribute to the network.

1007594537018187777.text: 9/ E.g. If a system relies on a finite set of agents, (such as DPoS or a tokenised public PoA network), then there is a clear reliance on the efforts of others to secure the financial wellbeing of token holders.

1007594535835357184.text: 8/ Also, how decentralised is decentralised enough? My suspicion is that it's not about hard numbers, but about system design.

1007594534505676801.text: 7/ I wonder how regulators will think about these well intentioned projects during this liminal period? The Commissioner's statement gives me hope that they are likely to view these projects charitably.

1007594532568027136.text: 6/ If a protocol can only work given a liquid native token, it is likely that there will always be some liminal period after mainnet launch, but before widespread adoption, in which the tokens may be regarded as investment contracts.
